.SHORT TERM...
Issued at 148 AM PDT Wed Jul 22 2026
(Today and tonight)

Low clouds and the leading edge of cooler air on southwesterly
winds with the eastern side of the northward moving remnant low
(once part of tropical storm Elida) rapidly moved to and filled in
along the coast Tuesday afternoon and evening. The remnant low is
still enveloped by a tropical air mass, but it also has had time
to draw in cooler air into the circulation from the northwest.
This is the air that`ll cool our temperatures today, but it`ll
also feel muggy and damp today. There may even be a few patches of
light drizzle/light rain in the newly arriving moisture rich and
cooler air mass combination.

Since about 8 pm to 10 pm Tuesday, an increase in surface dewpoint
temperatures (higher water vapor) has spread across about the entire
forecast area. Dewpoint temperatures in the 50s and 60s are now
widespread.

An area of increasing larger scale subsidence and a clearing sky
coincided with maximum diurnal surface heating on Tuesday, boosting
daytime highs well above normal including breaking several record
high temperatures in our forecast area for July 21st. However,
other long term stations such as Santa Rosa, San Francisco, Napa,
Kentfield, San Jose and Livermore with a period of record back
including July 1917 were in the middle of a several day heat wave
this time in 1917; none of these stations reached record highs on
Tuesday.

Daytime highs today will be noticeably cooler even far inland:
60s/70s coastside to the 70s/80 bayside and 80s/90s far inland.
Lows in the 50s to lower 60s tonight.

